isi

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict isi with group and time_point (formula: isi ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.54) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.25. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 13.53 (S.E. = 0.27, p < .001, 95% CI [13.01, 14.05]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.13, S.E. = 0.38, p = 0.734, 95% CI [-0.87, 0.61]; Std. beta = -0.03, 95% CI [-0.21, 0.15])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.47, S.E. = 0.36, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.18, -1.76]; Std. beta = -0.60, 95% CI [-0.77, -0.43])
  • The effect of time point [3rd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.61, S.E. = 1.21, p = 0.616, 95% CI [-2.97, 1.76]; Std. beta = -0.15, 95% CI [-0.72, 0.43])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -2.91, S.E. = 0.54, p < .001, 95% CI [-3.97, -1.85]; Std. beta = -0.71, 95% CI [-0.96, -0.45])
  • The interaction effect of time point [3rd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and negative (beta = -5.10, S.E. = 1.58, p = 0.001, 95% CI [-8.20, -2.01]; Std. beta = -1.24, 95% CI [-1.99, -0.49])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
